{% block content %}
<header>
  <span class="icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-place-of-worship"></i></span>
  <h1>Practices &amp; Worship</h1>
  <p>Beyond doctrine: what Latter-day Saint life actually looks like — Sunday services, the temple, daily devotion, and the rhythms of an active member's week.</p>
</header>

<main>

  <div class="intro-banner">
    <strong>Lived faith.</strong> Where the comparison pages focus on what Latter-day Saints <em>believe</em>, this page describes what they <em>do</em>. LDS practice is highly participatory — there is no paid local clergy, and ordinary members run congregations, teach lessons, and serve one another in assigned roles called "callings."
  </div>

  <!-- Meetinghouse vs Temple -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-building-columns"></i> &nbsp;Two Kinds of Sacred Space</div>
  <p style="font-size:0.95rem; color:var(--muted); margin-bottom:1.2rem; line-height:1.7;">A common point of confusion: LDS chapels and LDS temples are <em>not</em> the same thing and serve entirely different purposes.</p>
  <div class="vs-grid">
    <div class="vs-box">
      <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-church"></i> Meetinghouse (Chapel)</h3>
      <span class="vs-sub">Open to everyone</span>
      <ul>
        <li>The ordinary weekly place of worship, found in most neighborhoods</li>
        <li>Anyone — member or not — is welcome to attend Sunday services</li>
        <li>Hosts Sacrament meeting, Sunday classes, youth activities, and social events</li>
        <li>Plain and functional in design; no admission requirements</li>
        <li>A local congregation is called a <em>ward</em> (or smaller, a <em>branch</em>)</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
    <div class="vs-box temple">
      <h3><i class="fa-solid fa-place-of-worship"></i> Temple</h3>
      <span class="vs-sub">Reserved for sacred ordinances</span>
      <ul>
        <li>A small number of dedicated buildings, not used for weekly worship</li>
        <li>Entry requires a "temple recommend" — a certificate of worthiness</li>
        <li>Site of the most sacred ordinances: endowment, sealing (eternal marriage), and proxy baptism for the dead</li>
        <li>Ornate and set apart; closed on Sundays</li>
        <li>Members regard temple worship as the highest expression of their faith</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- A typical Sunday -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-calendar-day"></i> &nbsp;A Typical Sunday</div>
  <p style="font-size:0.95rem; color:var(--muted); margin-bottom:1.2rem; line-height:1.7;">Since 2019, Sunday services follow a two-hour format that alternates each week. A visitor would experience something like this:</p>
  <div class="step-list">
    <div class="step-item">
      <div class="step-time">~60 min</div>
      <div class="step-body">
        <h4>Sacrament Meeting</h4>
        <p>The main worship service, open to all. Includes hymns, prayers, the blessing and passing of the sacrament (bread and water in remembrance of Christ), and "talks" — sermons given by ordinary assigned members rather than professional clergy.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="step-item">
      <div class="step-time">~50 min</div>
      <div class="step-body">
        <h4>Second Hour (alternating weekly)</h4>
        <p>On the first and third Sundays, <strong>Sunday School</strong> — scripture study classes by age group. On the second and fourth Sundays, <strong>Priesthood / Relief Society</strong> — separate instructional meetings for men and women focused on gospel living and service.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="step-item">
      <div class="step-time">Concurrent</div>
      <div class="step-body">
        <h4>Primary &amp; Youth Classes</h4>
        <p>Children (Primary) and teenagers attend their own age-appropriate classes during the second hour, learning scripture stories, music, and gospel principles.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Daily and weekly practices -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-sun"></i> &nbsp;Daily &amp; Weekly Devotion</div>
  <div class="practice-grid">
    <div class="practice-card">
      <span class="pc-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-hands-praying"></i></span>
      <h3>Personal &amp; Family Prayer</h3>
      <p>Members are encouraged to pray individually and as families, typically morning and evening, and to offer a blessing on meals.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-card">
      <span class="pc-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-book-bible"></i></span>
      <h3>Scripture Study</h3>
      <p>Daily reading of the standard works (Bible, Book of Mormon, Doctrine &amp; Covenants, Pearl of Great Price) is a central habit, often following the church-wide "Come, Follow Me" curriculum.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-card">
      <span class="pc-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-house-chimney"></i></span>
      <h3>Home Evening</h3>
      <p>Monday evenings are traditionally reserved for family time, lessons, and activities at home, free of church meetings.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-card">
      <span class="pc-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-utensils"></i></span>
      <h3>Monthly Fast</h3>
      <p>On the first Sunday of each month, members fast for two meals and donate the cost (a "fast offering") to help the poor.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-card">
      <span class="pc-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-mug-hot"></i></span>
      <h3>Word of Wisdom</h3>
      <p>A daily health code: members abstain from alcohol, tobacco, coffee, tea, and illegal drugs, and are counseled toward moderation and healthy living.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-card">
      <span class="pc-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-hand-holding-dollar"></i></span>
      <h3>Tithing</h3>
      <p>Members contribute 10% of their income to the church, a requirement for holding a temple recommend.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-card">
      <span class="pc-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-people-carry-box"></i></span>
      <h3>Ministering</h3>
      <p>Members are assigned to watch over and regularly visit a few households, offering practical and spiritual support.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="practice-card">
      <span class="pc-icon"><i class="fa-solid fa-clipboard-list"></i></span>
      <h3>Callings</h3>
      <p>Nearly every active member holds a volunteer "calling" — teaching, leadership, music, clerical, or youth work — staffing the congregation without paid clergy.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Ordinances and milestones -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-route"></i> &nbsp;Ordinances &amp; Life Milestones</div>
  <div class="narrative">
    <p><strong>Baptism &amp; confirmation (age 8+).</strong> Children of members are typically baptized by immersion at age eight, the "age of accountability," and then confirmed members and given the gift of the Holy Ghost by the laying on of hands.</p>
    <p><strong>Priesthood ordination.</strong> Worthy young men may be ordained to the Aaronic Priesthood beginning around age 11–12, advancing through offices (deacon, teacher, priest) and later to the Melchizedek Priesthood. Women are not ordained to the priesthood but lead the global women's Relief Society and other organizations.</p>
    <p><strong>Missionary service.</strong> Many young adults serve full-time missions — typically two years for young men (from age 18) and 18 months for young women (from age 19) — at their own or their family's expense, often in another country and language.</p>
    <p><strong>Temple endowment &amp; sealing.</strong> Adults who are prepared and hold a temple recommend receive the "endowment" (a ceremony of covenants and instruction) and may be "sealed" in marriage, which Latter-day Saints believe binds families together for eternity, not only for this life.</p>
    <p><strong>Garments.</strong> Adults who have received the endowment wear a special temple garment under their clothing as a reminder of the covenants they have made — a private practice often misunderstood by outsiders.</p>
  </div>

  <!-- Organization note -->
  <div class="section-head"><i class="fa-solid fa-sitemap"></i> &nbsp;How a Congregation Is Organized</div>
  <div class="narrative">
    <p>Local congregations are geographic. A <strong>ward</strong> (a few hundred members) is led by a <strong>bishop</strong> — an unpaid volunteer who serves for several years while keeping his regular job. Several wards form a <strong>stake</strong>, led by a stake president. Smaller or newer congregations are called <strong>branches</strong>.</p>
    <p>Above the local level, the church is led globally by a <strong>President</strong> (regarded as a living prophet), two counselors forming the First Presidency, and the <strong>Quorum of the Twelve Apostles</strong>. Because there is no professional local clergy, the work of running the church falls to ordinary members serving in rotating callings — a defining feature of Latter-day Saint community life.</p>
  </div>

</main>

<footer>
  This page is for educational and informational purposes. Practices are summarized in good faith from official church sources and may vary by region and over time. &copy; 2026
</footer>
{% endblock %}
